It checks that all classes have a public method named foo and do not have a public method named bar. You can also use the ArchUnitRunner for JUnit tests.

ArchUnit rules are based on classes, but you can ask your `api` instance for its class (`api.getClass()`).

Full example for [JUnit4](https://www.archunit.org/userguide/html/000_Index.html#_junit_support) (for JUnit5, just drop the `ArchUnitRunner`):

```java
