&gt; How can I set the values sequentially like this?

`HttpSecurity` internally has a list of  `SecurityConfigurer` to configure different parts of `HttpSecurity`.  You can think that the methods on it such as `csrf()` , `headers()` or `authorizeRequests()` etc. just return one of these `SecurityConfigurer` for you to configure. It allows to configure the value sequentially just because it implements the [method chaining][1] by returning &#39;this&#39; instance. 

&gt; Is it coming as null first and I set the configuration values from the
&gt; start? or it has default values and I complete it?


`HttpSecurity` is a bean that is defined by in [`HttpSecurityConfiguration`][2] . Spring Boot will somehow enable it through `@EnableWebSecurity`. Now if you look its source codes , it defines the `HttpSecurity` bean as the followings : 

``` java
HttpSecurity httpSecurity() throws Exception {
		WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter.LazyPasswordEncoder passwordEncoder = new WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter.LazyPasswordEncoder(
				this.context);
		AuthenticationManagerBuilder authenticationBuilder = new WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter.DefaultPasswordEncoderAuthenticationManagerBuilder(
				this.objectPostProcessor, passwordEncoder);
		authenticationBuilder.parentAuthenticationManager(authenticationManager());
		authenticationBuilder.authenticationEventPublisher(getAuthenticationEventPublisher());
		HttpSecurity http = new HttpSecurity(this.objectPostProcessor, authenticationBuilder, createSharedObjects());
		// @formatter:off
		http
			.csrf(withDefaults())
			.addFilter(new WebAsyncManagerIntegrationFilter())
			.exceptionHandling(withDefaults())
			.headers(withDefaults())
			.sessionManagement(withDefaults())
			.securityContext(withDefaults())
			.requestCache(withDefaults())
			.anonymous(withDefaults())
			.servletApi(withDefaults())
			.apply(new DefaultLoginPageConfigurer&lt;&gt;());
		http.logout(withDefaults());
		// @formatter:on
		applyDefaultConfigurers(http);
		return http;
	}
```

So it has already defined some default value. You then define the `filterChain` bean to override some of the default value based on your application security requirement.

&gt; How it sets the values in multi-calls without overwriting the previous
&gt; values? what is this approach name in Java? Can I do the same with my
&gt; objects?

It depends on the implementation of that method. Some method will overwrite the previous value such as `http.csrf().disable()` while some method will add one more configuration to the related `SecurityConfigurer` such as `http.authorizeRequests().mvcMatchers(&quot;api/**&quot;).authenticated()`.


This approach is use method chaining to build a [DSL-like API][3] for configuring the `HttpSecurity`.


&gt; Is there a way that I can see what are its current values?

As `HttpSecurity` is a bean , that means you can define a spring bean and inject it into this bean such that you can navigate and access its internal structure to see its current value. 

For example, implement a `CommandLineRunner` which will execute at the application startup is a nice way to go : 

``` java
@Component
public class MyCommandLineRunner implement CommandLineRunner {
	
	@Autowired
	private HttpSecurity httpSecurity;

	public void run(String... args) throws Exception {
		//access httpSecurity to see if current value.
	}

}
```

  [1]: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/method-chaining-in-java-with-examples/
  [2]: https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-security/blob/7e0fcb7daeb19543e90aa0375308b4bd67f70b94/config/src/main/java/org/springframework/security/config/annotation/web/configuration/HttpSecurityConfiguration.java#L105C48-L105C48
  [3]: https://illegalexception.schlichtherle.de/patterns/2013/06/06/on-domain-specific-languages-in-java-part-1-method-chaining/

